duobus Lucullis] (i) L. Licinius Lucullus Ponticus, cos. B.C. 74 with M. Aurelius Cotta, a very able general, who conducted campaigns under great disadvantages against Mithridates and Tigranes in 69—67. His well earned triumph was delayed till 63, cp. Acad. 11. 3. See the admirable account of his campaign iu Mommsen IV. c. 2. (ii) his brother M. Terentius Varro Lucullus cos. B.C. 73 with C. Cassius Varus. He gained some victories in Thrace for which he was allowed the honour of a triumph in 71.

M. Crasso] M. Licinius Crassus, who on account of his great wealth received the agnomen of Dives, was consul with Cn. Pompeius twice, in 70 and in 55. In 60 he was one of the first triumvirate which consisted of Caesar, Pompey and Crassus. He was defeated by the Parthians and slain in battle near Carrhae in Mesopotamia in 54: cp. above ξ 7.

Q. Hortensio] cos. B.c. 69 with Q. Caecilius Metellus. He was next to Cicero the greatest Roman advocate: he died in 50.

C. Curioni] C. Scribonius Curi0‚ father of the Curio often mentioned in this speech. He was consul in 76 with Cn. Octavius. He fought against the Maesians and Dardanians, and was the first Roman general who reached the Danube: he died in 53. For his praise of Cicero’s consulship cp. Att.
